President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the State of Mississippi and authorized Federal assistance for recovery efforts following severe storms, tornadoes, straight-line winds, and flooding that occurred from April 13 to April 14, 2019. The Federal funding will be available to State and eligible local governments, as well as certain private nonprofit organizations, for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties of Clarke, Clay, Itawamba, Kemper, Monroe, Oktibbeha, Warren, and Yazoo are specifically mentioned as being affected. Hazard mitigation measures statewide will also receive Federal funding on a cost-sharing basis. Jose M. Girot has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. Additional designations may be made if requested by the State and further damage assessments warrant it. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk.